<h1>Stephen Voida</h1>
	<img src='../images/people/SteveVoida.jpg'  alt='Stephen Voida' class='fltlft' />
<p>
	<span style="font-size:12px;"><span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Stephen Voida is a research scientist in the Department of Informatics at the University of California, Irvine and is collaborating with Gloria Mark and with Gary and Judy Olson as a member of Hana &#39;Ohana. Previously, he worked with <a href="http://pages.cpsc.ucalgary.ca/~saul" target="_blank">Saul Greenberg</a> and <a href="http://pages.cpsc.ucalgary.ca/~sheelagh/" target="_blank">Sheelagh Carpendale</a> as a postdoctoral fellow at the <a href="http://www.cpsc.ucalgary.ca/" target="_blank">University of Calgary</a>. He holds a Ph.D. in Computer Science and an M.S. in Human&ndash;Computer Interaction from the <a href="http://gvu.gatech.edu/" target="_blank">Georgia Institute of Technology</a> and a B.S. in Computer Science from <a href="http://engineering.asu.edu/cidse" target="_blank">Arizona State University</a>. His research on activity-centered computing and large-scale interactive displays has been supported by the <a href="http://www.nsf.gov" target="_blank">NSF</a>, <a href="http://www.nserc-crsng.gc.ca/index_eng.asp" target="_blank">NSERC</a>, Alberta&rsquo;s <a href="http://www.ucalgary.ca/research/funding/iCORE" target="_blank"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; font-style: italic; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; ">iCORE</span></a><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap; "> provincial research initiative, <a href="http://smarttech.com/" target="_blank">SMART Technologies</a>, <a href="http://www.ibm.com" target="_blank">IBM</a>, <a href="http://rii.ricoh.com/" target="_blank">Ricoh Innovations</a>, and <a href="http://www.steelcase.com/" target="_blank">Steelcase</a>.</span></span></span></p>
<p>
	<span style="font-size:12px;"><span style="font-family:arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Stephen designs, implements, and studies the use of human&ndash;computer interfaces for information work. His research explores how information systems can better respond to the critical, real-world challenges of multitasking, information management, information sharing, and long-term information curation. He is currently leading an in-depth study of multitasking within small groups, examining the role of e-mail as a catalyst for task switching and a mechanism for task coordination, and is interested in exploring the ways that smartphones might be used as a hub for collecting, managing, and sharing information about individuals&rsquo; ongoing activities with their friends and co-workers.</span></span></p>
<p><a target='_blank' href='https://students.ics.uci.edu/~svoida'>https://students.ics.uci.edu/~svoida</a></p><br clear="all" />
<h2 class="gap">Publications</h2>
<ul> 
    	      <li>Mark, G., Voida, S. &amp; Cardello, A.V. (to appear). &ldquo;A pace not dictated by electrons&rdquo;: An empirical study of work without email. To appear in Proceedings of the SIGCHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems (CHI 2012), Austin, Texas, May 5&ndash;10.</li>
         	      <li>Hincapi√©-Ramos, J.D., Voida, S. &amp; Mark, G. (2011). A design space analysis of availability-sharing systems In Proceedings of the 24th ACM Symposium on User Interface Software and Technology (UIST 2011, pp. 85&ndash;96), Santa Barbara, California, October 16&ndash;19.</li>
         	      <li>Goecks, J., Voida, A., Voida, S. &amp; Mynatt, E.D. (2008). <em>Charitable technologies: Opportunities for collaborative computing in nonprofit fundraising</em>. In Proceedings of the ACM Conference on Computer-Supported Cooperative Work (CSCW 2008). San Diego, California, November 8-12. New York: ACM Press, pp. 689-698.</li>
       </ul>
